			25 Jan 2012 at 6:35 pm</a>		</div>

		<p>My interpretation of those documents &#8211; which I actually used as the basis for previous comment &#8211; is that you are *indeed* serving XHTML, though not in the sense that there&#8217;s an XHTML5 DOCTYPE.Â Perhaps a clearer way to explain it is to say that XHTML5 has been redefined to mean &#8220;HTML syntax served with an application/xhtml+xml content type and parsed according to the rules of XML well-formedness.&#8221;Â Now in terms of coding practices, again: that means using /&gt; to close *void* elements &#8212; img, meta, br, hr &#8212; is fine, but not necessary in HTML5. It becomes mandatory, however, if you&#8217;re serving those pages with an Â application/xhtml+xml content type.But using /&gt; to close elements such as a or span *is not* valid &#8220;XHTML5,&#8221; even though it is certainly valid XHTML1.0.Â </p>

